  <h1 id="top">Covariance &amp; Pearson Correlation</h1>
  <p>How two random variables move together. Drag points in the interactive scatter plot to see covariance and $r$ update live. The key GATE trap — uncorrelated ≠ independent — is built into the nonlinear preset.</p>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 1: JOINT DISTRIBUTIONS ═══ -->
<h2 id="joint">Theory — Joint Distributions &amp; Independence</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  When two variables are measured together, their <strong>joint</strong> distribution encodes every combination. Marginals collapse the joint to one variable; independence means the joint factorizes completely.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Joint PMF / PDF</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$p(x,y) = P(X\!=\!x,\, Y\!=\!y), \quad \sum_x\sum_y p(x,y) = 1$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Continuous: $f(x,y)\ge0$, $\iint f(x,y)\,dx\,dy=1$. Probabilities are volumes under the surface.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Marginals — collapse one variable</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$p_X(x) = \sum_y p(x,y) \qquad f_X(x) = \int f(x,y)\,dy$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">In a PMF table: row totals → $p_X$, column totals → $p_Y$. Always compute marginals first.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Independence — factorization test</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$p(x,y) = p_X(x)\cdot p_Y(y) \quad \text&#123;for ALL &#125;(x,y)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">One cell failure → dependent. Also: support must be a <em>rectangle</em> — triangular support ($0 &lt; y &lt; x$) forces dependence even if the formula looks separable.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Consequence of independence</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$X,Y \text&#123; independent &#125;\Rightarrow E[XY] = E[X]\cdot E[Y]$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">And generally $E[g(X)h(Y)]=E[g(X)]\cdot E[h(Y)]$ for any functions $g, h$.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 2: COVARIANCE ═══ -->
<h2 id="covariance">Theory — Covariance</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Covariance measures how much $X$ and $Y$ deviate from their means <em>together</em>. It has units (unlike $r$) and can be any real number.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Definition — computational form</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y) = E[XY] - E[X]E[Y]$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Equivalent to $E[(X-\mu_X)(Y-\mu_Y)]$. Use the computational form in calculations — it's faster.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Variance of a linear combination</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Var&#125;(aX+bY) = a^2\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) + b^2\text&#123;Var&#125;(Y) + 2ab\,\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">GATE trap: forgetting the $2ab\,\text&#123;Cov&#125;$ term when $X, Y$ are not independent.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Bilinearity — constants factor out</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Cov&#125;(aX+b,\; cY+d) = ac\cdot\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Additive constants $b, d$ disappear entirely. Only the multiplicative scalars $a, c$ matter.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Special values</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,X) = \text&#123;Var&#125;(X) \qquad \text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y)=\text&#123;Cov&#125;(Y,X)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Diagonal of the covariance matrix = variances. Off-diagonal entries are symmetric.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">$E[XY]$ shortcut for Bernoulli variables</span>
    For Bernoulli $X$ and $Y$: $E[XY] = P(X=1 \text&#123; and &#125; Y=1)$ — a joint probability, no double sum needed. Extends to any $X, Y$ that are independent: $E[XY] = E[X]E[Y]$, so $\text&#123;Cov&#125; = 0$.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 3: CORRELATION & TRAP ═══ -->
<h2 id="correlation">Theory — Correlation &amp; the Key Trap</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Correlation is covariance rescaled to $[-1,1]$ — it removes units and makes linear association comparable across problems. But it only detects <em>linear</em> relationships.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Pearson correlation — scale-free</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\rho = \frac&#123;\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y)&#125;&#123;\sigma_X\,\sigma_Y&#125;, \qquad -1 \le \rho \le 1$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Dimensionless. Scale $X$ or $Y$ by any positive constant — $\rho$ is unchanged (unlike Cov).</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Boundary values</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\lvert\rho\rvert = 1 \iff Y = aX+b \text&#123; (perfect line)&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$\rho=+1$: positive slope $a>0$. $\rho=-1$: negative slope $a&lt;0$. A curve can have $|\rho|&lt;1$ even if deterministic.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Independent ⇒ Uncorrelated (one way only)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$X,Y \text&#123; independent &#125;\Rightarrow \text&#123;Cov&#125;=0 \Rightarrow \rho=0$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Contrapositive: $\rho\ne0$ → definitely dependent. But $\rho=0$ says nothing about independence.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Uncorrelated ≠ Independent (the GATE trap)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\rho = 0 \;\nRightarrow\; \text&#123;independent&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$Y=X^2$, $X\sim\text&#123;Uniform&#125;(-1,1)$: $\rho=0$ yet $Y$ is fully determined by $X$. (2026 Q63)</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">The headline 2026 Q63 trap — nonlinear dependence hides from $\rho$</span>
    $\rho=0$ means no <em>linear</em> association. A symmetric nonlinear relationship — $Y=X^2$ on $[-1,1]$ — produces $\text&#123;Cov&#125;=0$ via $E[X^3]=0$ (odd function) even though $Y$ is fully determined by $X$. Load the "Nonlinear" preset below to see $r\approx0$ despite a clear parabolic pattern.
  </div>
</div>

