<!-- ═══ WORKED EXAMPLES ═══ -->
<h2 id="examples">Worked Examples</h2>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 1 · Discrete joint table — marginals, Cov, ρ, independence</span>
    <p>Joint PMF of $(X,Y)$: $p(0,0)=0.1$, $p(0,1)=0.2$, $p(1,0)=0.3$, $p(1,1)=0.4$. Find the marginals, test independence, compute $\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y)$ and $\rho$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Marginals (row/column totals):</strong> $p_X(0)=0.3,\; p_X(1)=0.7$; &nbsp; $p_Y(0)=0.4,\; p_Y(1)=0.6$.</p>
    <p><strong>Independence?</strong> $p(0,0)=0.1$ vs $p_X(0)\cdot p_Y(0)=0.12$. Not equal → <strong>dependent</strong>.</p>
    <p><strong>Means:</strong> $E[X]=0.7$, $E[Y]=0.6$.</p>
    <p><strong>$E[XY]$:</strong> only the $X=1,Y=1$ cell contributes: $E[XY]=(1)(1)(0.4)=0.4$.</p>
    <p><strong>Covariance:</strong> $\text&#123;Cov&#125;=0.4-(0.7)(0.6)=0.4-0.42=-0.02$.</p>
    <p><strong>Variances:</strong> $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)=0.7\times0.3=0.21$; &nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(Y)=0.6\times0.4=0.24$.</p>
    <p><strong>Correlation:</strong> $\rho = \dfrac&#123;-0.02&#125;&#123;\sqrt&#123;0.21\times0.24&#125;&#125; = \dfrac&#123;-0.02&#125;&#123;0.2245&#125; \approx -0.089$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Pattern: marginals → $E[X],E[Y]$ → $E[XY]$ (sum all $xy\cdot p(x,y)$ cells) → Cov → ρ. This is the five-step drill for every PMF table.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Cov = −0.02 · ρ ≈ −0.089 · Dependent</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 2 · GATE 2024 Q65 — Covariance of two Bernoulli events (NAT)</span>
    <p>Two fair coins are tossed independently. $X=1$ if both are heads (else 0); $Y=1$ if at least one is a head (else 0). Find $\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y)$ to three decimals.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Identify distributions:</strong> $P(\text&#123;both heads&#125;)=\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;4&#125;\Rightarrow E[X]=\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;4&#125;$; &nbsp; $P(\text&#123;at least one head&#125;)=\tfrac&#123;3&#125;&#123;4&#125;\Rightarrow E[Y]=\tfrac&#123;3&#125;&#123;4&#125;$.</p>
    <p><strong>$E[XY]$:</strong> $XY=1$ only when $X=1$, which forces $Y=1$. So $E[XY]=P(\text&#123;both heads&#125;)=\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;4&#125;$.</p>
    <p><strong>Covariance:</strong> $\text&#123;Cov&#125; = E[XY]-E[X]E[Y] = \tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;4&#125;-\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;4&#125;\cdot\tfrac&#123;3&#125;&#123;4&#125; = \tfrac&#123;4&#125;&#123;16&#125;-\tfrac&#123;3&#125;&#123;16&#125; = \tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;16&#125; = 0.0625$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Shortcut: for Bernoullis, $E[XY]=P(X=1\text&#123; and &#125;Y=1)$. Positive Cov: both variables tend to be 1 together (both heads scenario). No joint table or integral needed.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Cov(X,Y) = 1/16 = 0.063</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 3 · GATE 2026 Q63 — Uncorrelated but dependent (NAT · Hard)</span>
    <p>$X\sim\text&#123;Uniform&#125;(-1,1)$. Given $X=x$, the conditional distribution is $Y\mid X=x \sim\text&#123;Uniform&#125;(x^2-0.1,\, x^2+0.1)$. Find $\text&#123;correlation&#125;(X,Y)$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Tower property — no double integral:</strong></p>
    <p>$E[Y\mid X=x] = x^2$ (midpoint of the conditional uniform). So $E[XY] = E[X\cdot E[Y\mid X]] = E[X\cdot X^2] = E[X^3]$.</p>
    <p>$E[X^3]=0$ because $X^3$ is an odd function on the symmetric interval $[-1,1]$.</p>
    <p>$E[X]=0$ (symmetric). So $\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y) = E[XY]-E[X]E[Y] = 0 - 0 = 0$, giving $\rho=0$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">$Y$ is fully governed by $X$ through $X^2$ — clearly dependent — yet $\rho=0$. Correlation sees only linear association; the dependence here is nonlinear (even function on a symmetric interval). This is the 2026 Q63 trap.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">ρ = 0 (uncorrelated, NOT independent)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 4 · Continuous joint PDF — marginal, independence, covariance</span>
    <p>$f(x,y) = x+y$ for $0\le x\le1,\; 0\le y\le1$ (else 0). Find $f_X(x)$, test independence, compute $\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y)$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Marginal:</strong> $f_X(x)=\int_0^1(x+y)\,dy = x+\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125;$ &nbsp;(by symmetry $f_Y(y)=y+\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125;$).</p>
    <p><strong>Independence?</strong> $f_X\cdot f_Y=\bigl(x+\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125;\bigr)\bigl(y+\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125;\bigr)= xy+\tfrac&#123;x&#125;&#123;2&#125;+\tfrac&#123;y&#125;&#123;2&#125;+\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;4&#125;\ne x+y$ → <strong>Dependent</strong>.</p>
    <p><strong>Means:</strong> $E[X]=\int_0^1 x\bigl(x+\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2&#125;\bigr)\,dx=\tfrac&#123;7&#125;&#123;12&#125;$ (and $E[Y]=\tfrac&#123;7&#125;&#123;12&#125;$).</p>
    <p><strong>$E[XY]$:</strong> $\iint xy(x+y)\,dx\,dy = \tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;6&#125;+\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;6&#125;=\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;3&#125;$.</p>
    <p><strong>Covariance:</strong> $\text&#123;Cov&#125;=\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;3&#125;-\bigl(\tfrac&#123;7&#125;&#123;12&#125;\bigr)^2=\tfrac&#123;48&#125;&#123;144&#125;-\tfrac&#123;49&#125;&#123;144&#125;=-\tfrac&#123;1&#125;&#123;144&#125;\approx-0.0069$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Method: integrate for marginal → factorization test → double integral for $E[XY]$ → covariance formula. The tiny negative Cov reflects a subtle anti-correlation in this PDF.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">f_X(x) = x + 1/2 · Dependent · Cov = −1/144 ≈ −0.0069</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ GATE ANGLE ═══ -->
<div class="gd-gate-box">
  <div class="gd-gate-box__title">GATE DA Angle</div>
  <p><strong>The headline trap:</strong> $\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y)=0$ does NOT imply independence. Correlation only captures <em>linear</em> association. A symmetric nonlinear dependence — $Y=X^2$ on $[-1,1]$ — gives $\rho=0$ even though $Y$ is fully determined by $X$. 2026 Q63 is built entirely on this.</p>
  <p><strong>Computational formula:</strong> $\text&#123;Cov&#125;=E[XY]-E[X]E[Y]$. For Bernoulli variables, $E[XY]=P(X=1\text&#123; and &#125;Y=1)$ — no table needed. (2024 Q65)</p>
  <p><strong>Var of a sum — always include Cov:</strong> $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X+Y)=\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)+\text&#123;Var&#125;(Y)+2\,\text&#123;Cov&#125;(X,Y)$. Set Cov=0 only when independence is given. MCQ trap: answer (A) often omits the covariance term entirely.</p>
  <p><strong>Tower property shortcut:</strong> If $E[Y\mid X]$ is known, use $E[XY]=E[X\cdot E[Y\mid X]]$ instead of a double integral. Saved 2026 Q63 in two lines versus computing $\iint xy\,f(x,y)\,dx\,dy$.</p>
  <p><strong>Independence requires rectangular support.</strong> If the support is triangular ($0&lt;y&lt;x$), the variables are dependent even if the formula looks separable — the range of $y$ depends on $x$.</p>
  <p><strong>Five-step PMF drill:</strong> (1) row/column totals → marginals; (2) $E[X],E[Y]$ from marginals; (3) $E[XY]=\sum\sum xy\cdot p(x,y)$; (4) $\text&#123;Cov&#125;=E[XY]-E[X]E[Y]$; (5) $\rho=\text&#123;Cov&#125;/(\sigma_X\sigma_Y)$.</p>
</div>

